Overall, Congress' approach to dealing with the narcotics traffic abroad may be characterized as oriented toward: (1) reduction of supply, (2) bilateral arrangements (as opposed to multilateral ones), and (3) a preference for the "stick" rather than the "carrot." The Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1988 may signal major changes in US narco-policy in these three areas.
CONGRESSIONALROLEIN INTERNATIONAL NARCOTICSCONTROLAS PARTOF AN OVERALL EXPANDED ROLEIN FOREIGNPOLICY

THE US CONSTITUTION DIVIDES the power to make foreign policy between the executive and legislative branches, but in such a way that each branch shares in the process and plays an important, though differing, role;1 however, the question of precisely which branch has final responsibility is not clearly defined. At some times, the Congress may delegate certain functions to the
executive while claiming those functions for itself at others. What is clear is that although the executive branch is entrusted with the execution of foreign policy, the two branches constantly influence, and interact with, one another (Collier, 1986; Frank and
Weisband, 1979). Since the early 1970s, Congress has asserted (and expanded)
its role in foreign policy. This development has been based primarily on its constitutional powers to declare war, to regulate foreign commerce, and to make appropriations (i.e., the "power of the purse"). Three noteworthy examples of such efforts include passage of the War Powers Resolution, the 1976 amendments to the Arms Export Control Act, and the 1975 amendments to the Foreign Assistance Act. These measures ascribe to the Congress an active role in (1) decisions to deploy troops, (2) the sale of arms to foreign entities, and (3) the determination of standards of conduct, particularly in the area of human rights, as a requirement of
eligibility for foreign states to receive US assistance. This role of the Congress as a leading actor in the development
of US narcotics policy must be evaluated within (a) the general context of a domestic furor over drug abuse and (b) an ongoing - and, in recent decades, accelerated - tug-of-war between the executive and legislative branches over control of foreign policy.

