CONGRESSIONAL ROLE SHAPED AND LIMITED BY LEGISLATIVEORGANIZATIONAL STRUCTURE

INTERNATIONAL NARCOTICS CONTROL is a multifaceted
problem. It may be approached as a foreign relations problem, as a family and/or health problem, as a law enforcement problem, as a defense/national security problem, as a problem in judicial rules and practices, as an allocation of resources problem, as a regional and/or border problem, as an agricultural and foreign trade problem,3 as a banking problem, as an intelligence problem, as a science and research problem, and as a terrorism-connected
problem. Congress deals with national problems through a network of
standing committees, select committees, special caucuses, working groups and task forces. Generally, committee jurisdictions reflect the complex network of agencies in the executive branch which congressional committees fund and oversee. Altogether, there is a total of 53 committees and subcommittees in the House
of Representatives and 21 committees and subcommittees in the Senate which currently have jurisdiction over some aspect of the US national drug-abuse policy (Hardy, 1988).
