THE CONGRESSIONAL ROLE IN INTERNATIONAL NARCOTICS CONTROL LEGISLATION

POLLS IN THE FIRSTHALFOF 1988 show that the US general public considers drug control to be the number one issue of domestic concern, and that nearly half of all US respondents regard the drug trafficas the country's number one international problem as well (New York Times, 1988). Because the Congress is aware of this ongoing public concern, it has taken an active role
in designing legislation which governs and implements a narcotics control policy for the United States.5
Congress may initiate new narco-policy by using legislation to establish new programs, to condition and limit spending, to set
new objectives and guidelines, and to authorize and direct the executive branch to undertake certain specific activities. Most
noteworthy of such legislative initiatives are the provisions governing control of the international narcotics trade which appear in the Anti-DrugAbuse Acts of 1986 and 1988, and which impose sanctions on countries who play major roles in the production or transshipmentof illicitdrugs and areuncooperative in the control effort.6 These provisions represent a major policy reversal of roles previously played by the Congress and the president in the decision to deny assistance to certain drug-producing
or drug-transitingcountries. Under previous legislation, the president took the initiative in determining whether or not a country would be eligible for foreign assistance. Under the new law, Con-
gress now takes the initiative in making the determination as to
which categories of countries will not receive aid, while the role of the president has been reduced to either enforcing the terms
of, or seeking exceptions to, this congressional determination.7 The Anti-DrugAbuse Acts of 1986 and 1988 link the coopera-
tion of source countries (drug-producing and/or -transiting countries) with the United States in controlling this trafficto the eligibility of those countries for US foreign aid, and under certain circumstances, for US trade benefits. This process, commonly

