Two other oversight mechanisms, in addition to hearings, are notification and reporting. Notification requires that an official of the executive branch (usually the president) report to Congress when a specified event occurs. Reporting usually requires that specific information be submitted to the Congress as a formal report, which may be either a one-time event or required on aperiodic basis (Collier, 1988). In March 1986, the Congressional Research Service (of the Library of Congress) identified 19 reporting/notification requirements which were related to the issue of international narcotics control. In September 1988, similar research revealed that the number of such requirements, in law, had risen from 19 to 34, an increase of almost 79% in only two and a half years.15
Key notification requirements in this area relate to certification, i.e. determining which major illicit drug-producing/transiting countries should be exempt from congressionally-mandated sanctions (SEC. 481 [h] [1] [A] and SEC.481 [h] [5] of the Foreign Assis-
tance Act of 1961, PL 87-195, as amended, SEC.802, 803, and 804
of the Trade Act of 1974, PL 93-618, as amended, and SEC.2013 of
the Anti-Drug Abuse Act of 1986, PL99-570). By requiring that the president's list of exempt countries - and the reason for their exemption - be given to the Congress before becoming effective, the law affords the Congress an opportunity to monitor and explore the basis of, as well as rationale for, the president's determinations.
The most important of the periodic reporting requirements in this area is the one which mandates that the Department of State submit to the Congress annually, on 1 March, an International Narcotics Control Strategy Report (INCSR) (SEC.481 [e] of the Foreign Assistance Act of 1961). This report is critical to the certification process because the president bases his determinations of certification on the information it contains. The INCSR-- and its September Mid-Year Update (as set out by SEC.481 [b] [2]of the above Act) - are prepared by the Bureau of International Narcotics Mat-

