policy area, one which has become increasingly important to the US public. It is also likely that the Congress will continue to require new types of narcotics-related certification. New certification requirements concerning cooperation on money-laundering issues offer but one example of what may well prove to be an ongoing trend.
3. General Criteria for Certification. Formerly, Congress had instructed the president, when making his determinations of certification, to give foremost consideration to the ability of a foreign government to achieve the maximum reduction in its production of illicit drugs. However, the Congress has now downgraded the importance of this requirement to just one among many factors which the president must take into consideration. More and more, the Congress is engaged in adding new criteria for presidential consideration - such as having a bilateral narcotics agreement with the US, or taking necessary law enforcement steps to curb corruption - which stress the overall degree of cooperation in this area and which, at least in part, emphasize cooperation on law enforcement as a factor when making determinations of certification.
4. Country-Specific Criteria for Certification. Congress is
increasingly using legislation to establish cooperation "milestones" to guide the president in his certification of certain specific countries. Traditionally, such country-specific guidelines have been enacted for Bolivia, Jamaica, Mexico, and Peru. The 1988
Anti-Drug Abuse Act omits Jamaica but includes special criteria for Bolivia, Mexico, Pakistan, and Peru. Although not singled out by name, the 1988 Act also, in effect, includes special certification requirements for India and Turkey.
5. Types of Assistance Exempt from Certification Process. Congress is now examining whether to exempt from certification sanctions that assistance which, directly or indirectly, promotes anti-narcotics programs and goals. The 1988 Anti-Drug Abuse Act exempts from certification sanctions any assistance which has been designated for narcotics education/awareness activities. Congress can be expected to examine whether it should exempt from sanctions, as well, regional development projects of the US Agency for International Development (AID) which promote narcotics-related crop-substitution and income-substitution programs. Another area coming under increasing scrutiny is

