43

whether - when the national interest requires - US Interational Military, Education, and Training (IMET) programs should also be exempt from narcotics-related sanctions.
6. Precursor Chemical Regulation. Congress may increase its level of activity in this area despite powerful opposition from business interests representing the chemical and other export industries. According to US Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA) sources, 95% of the chemicals required to process the cocaine reaching the United States are of US origin. Congress has tried to deal with this fact by providing, in Title VI of the 1988 AntiDrug Abuse Act, for the establishment of new record-keeping controls on export of such chemicals and of penalties for their diversion into the illicit marketplace.
7. Focus on Foreign Drug-Related Corruption. This is a topic with widespread popular appeal which is destined to command increased attention from the Congress. Drug-related corruption of foreign officials is already the subject of congressional reporting requirements, and the 1988 Anti-Drug Abuse Act includes it among the criteria to be applied by the president in arriving at a determination of certification.
8. Increased Multilateral Efforts. Congress is placing more emphasis on multilateral cooperation, consultation, and endeavors in the international "war on drugs." The 1988 Anti-Drug Abuse Act urges formation of regional anti-narcotics forces and a regional anti-narcotics training center, and stresses the need for an integrated regional plan to fight the international cocaine trade.
9. Use of Positive Incentives. Congress is slowly adding positive incentives to the "stick" of the certification process. For instance, the 1988 Anti-Drug Abuse Act provides that funds may be re-allocated from countries which have not been certified to
those designated as fully cooperating. The recently passed foreign aid bill for FY 1989 provides similar "carrots",such as earmarking $70 million dollars of assistance for narcotics control programs to be made available to Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Jamaica, and Peru (SEC.575 of HR 4637, Foreign Operations, FY 1989).
10. Institution of Preventive, Rather Than Reactive,
Policies. In the past, congressional international narco-policy has focused primarily on putting out today's fires, rather than seeking to prevent the fires of the future. In contrast, the 1988 Anti-Drug Abuse Act urges increased assistance for narcotics control to

