countries which today are minor illicit drug-transitcountries and which cooperate with the US in its efforts to control this traffic.
11. Changes in Funding and Resource Allocation. Con-
gress and the US public are much more sensitive than in the past to the symbiotic relationship which exists between drug-producing and drug-consuming nations. A consensus is emerging that major increases in funding are needed to combat the drug problem, and that resources may have to be shifted, gradually, away from a major reliance on reducing supply to greater efforts to reduce demand as well, and, consequently, to domestic - and, to a lesser extent, overseas - anti-drugprograms.The 1988 Anti-
Drug Abuse Act increases the overall level of funding authorized for anti-drugactivityby approximately $2.6 billion, with $506 million currentlyavailable for outlays under existing budgetary constraints.This $506 million is to be divided fairlyevenly between
programs designed to reduce supply and those which try to reduce demand. Since current funding allocates approximately 25%to demand-reduction and 75%to supply-reduction programs, the Act's initial funding provisions appear to indicate a gradual shift, by the Congress, to commit more resources to reducing
demand.
12. Increased Integration and Centralization of Policy. Congressional anti-drug policy, both national and international, increasingly stresses the need for a more integrated approach to the problem. Inherent in this approach is a gradual acknowledgment that neither interdiction alone, nor eradication alone, nor education or rehabilitationalone, holds the key to resolution
of the international drug problem. The drug problem is being viewed less as a LatinAmerican/Asian source problem and more
as one of a shifting global supply, meeting a growing global demand. The congressional response - via the 1988 Anti-Drug Abuse Act - has been to encourage integration of US anti-drug efforts abroad with those of the region, and to seek greater centralization and integration of US drug policy at home by creating an Office of National Drug Control Policy, to be led by a cabinet-level federal official.

